"Majorca Island":"Majorca Island, Trinidad and Tobago","Spain":"Spain","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Hugo","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized form of   Hugh  , used throughout the Middle Ages in official documents, and now enjoying a revival as a given name."],"variants":[]},{"name":"IV","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Vivian   and   Vivien ."],"variants":[{"name":"Vivien","meanings":["Earlier generally taken as a variant of the boy's name   Vivian  , but now also rarely used for boys. This spelling was quite common in Old French. Its use as a girl's name in the English-speaking world was influenced by  Tennyson's  Merlin and Vivien (  1859 ). This name, from Arthurian legend, may represent an altered form of a Celtic name (perhaps akin to the Irish Gaelic name <i>Béibhinn</i> ‘white lady’, pronounced ‘bee-<b>veen</b>’). The actress  Vivien Leigh  (  1913–67 ) was christened <i>Vivian</i>."]},{"name":"Vivian","meanings":["Originally a boy's name, from an Old French form of the Latin name <i>Vivianus</i> (probably a derivative of <i>vivus</i> ‘alive’), but now more frequent as a girl's name. The name was borne by a 5th-century bishop of Saintes in western France, remembered for protecting his people during the invasion of the Visigoths."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Hugo IV Comte d'Empúries was born after 1186, his father, Ponce III de Ampurias, was 8865 and his mother, Adelaida de Montcada, was 8863. He had at least 1 son and 2 daughters with Maria de Vilademuls. He died in April 1230, in Majorca Island, Trinidad and Tobago."},"et":{"AFT 1185–APR 1230":"pärast 1186–aprill 1230","1170–1230":"1170–1230","1186–1230":"1186–1230","1172–Female":"1172–Surnud","1205–1269":"1205–1269","1216–1277":"1216–1277","1218–Female":"1218–Surnud","1135–1200":"1135–1200","1136–Female":"1136–Surnu